The assassination of Ismail Haniyeh, the leader of Hamas, has been described as a 'humiliating blow' to Iran. According to experts, the attack was a clear message from Israel that it can strike within Iran's borders. Andrew Fox, a researcher at the Henry Jackson Society, said that Haniyeh's killing 'sends a very clear message to Iran about Israel's ability to strike within their borders.' Fox noted that Haniyeh had limited strategic significance as a target and could have been easily replaced, but his death still had symbolic significance. This is not the first time Israel has carried out operations within Iran's borders. In August 2020, Israeli agents assassinated Abdullah Ahmed Abdullah, a high-ranking member of Al-Qaeda, in the streets of Tehran. In November 2020, a Mossad team killed Mohsen Fakhrizadeh, an Iranian nuclear physicist who was believed to be leading Iran's nuclear program. Ameneh Mehvar, a regional expert on the Middle East at the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data Project (ACLED), said that the latest attack has 'badly damaged' Iran's reputation in the region. She added that it shows how deeply Israel has infiltrated Iran's intelligence circles. Farzan Sabet, a senior researcher at the Global Governance Centre and Sanctions and Sustainable Peace Hub in Geneva, predicted that Iran's credibility among its allies will be damaged and that it may be forced to retaliate to save face. Burcu Ozcelik, a senior security expert on the Middle East at the Royal United Services Institute, said that the attack on Haniyeh marks a new phase of risky games in the region. She added that it will have an impact on the entire region. Mehvar predicted that Iran will retaliate, but in a 'more severe' but 'proportional' manner, possibly with the help of its allies. Fox expects a 'small-scale' escalation of rocket attacks from Iranian agents in Yemen, Iraq, and Lebanon, followed by a return to the previous unstable status quo. He added that Iran will not want to escalate to the point where the West intervenes, as it did during the April rocket attacks, which were also a 'humiliating defeat' for Iran.
